{ @@HeaderStart@@Magnus Carlsen – Wang Hao, Wijk aan Zee 2011@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game illustrates White’s kingside attack with h2-h4-h5 after a trade on g6, where Black recaptures ...hxg6. } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Be3 e6 5. Nd2 Nd7 6. Ngf3 Bg6 7. Be2 Ne7 8. Nh4 c5 { More common is  8...Nf5  9.Nxf5   but not  9.Nxg6 ?!  Nxe3  10.fxe3  hxg6  11.Nf3  g5  when Black has good counterplay  9...Bxf5  when Black is likely to keep his bishop on the h7-b1 diagonal with a good position; this is similar to the game Babaev – Burmakin which we study later in this chapter. } 9. c3 Nc6 { It was not too late for  9...Nf5 !?  10.Nxg6   or  10.Nxf5  Bxf5  10...hxg6  11.Nf3  Nxe3  12.fxe3  g5 !?  with reasonable counterplay. } 10. Nxg6 hxg6 { This small structural change must not be taken lightly. On the plus side, the capture ...hxg6 gives additional support to f5 while opening the h-file. Both these factors make the f4-f5 break harder to achieve. On the negative side, a black pawn on g6 means White can break on the kingside with h2-h4-h5 to later invade down the h-file. Now that we understand how the structure affects the plans, we proceed with the game. } 11. Nf3 { White will not gain much from f4-f5, for example, after  11.O-O  Be7  12.f4  Qb6  13.Qb3  cxd4  14.Qxb6  Nxb6  15.cxd4  O-O  16.g4  Rac8  17.f5  gxf5  18.gxf5  exf5  19.Rxf5  Black’s kingside is safe, and after  19...Nb4 !?  it is White who must fight for equality. } 11... Rc8 { Black will not be able to secure a safe place for his king, as he can no longer castle long.   As Postny points out, the variation  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  Qa5+  is nothing special for Black, as after  13.Kf1 !  += White will proceed with g2-g3, h2-h4 and  Kg2  which is similar to the game.   An independent try is  11...Qc7 !?  12.O-O  Be7  13.g3  O-O-O  14.Kg2  Kb8  15.Bf4  += when White has a comfortable advantage, though Black is solid for now. } 12. O-O a6 { The plan is ...b7-b5-b4 or ...c5-c4, but this is far too slow. } 13. g3 Be7 14. h4 { += Launching a kingside attack; Black needs to react quickly. } 14... b5 { Black cannot castle safely as after  14...O-O  15.Kg2  Qb6  16.Rb1  cxd4  17.cxd4  Na5  18.Rh1  Nc4  19.Bf4 !  the break h4-h5 yields a very strong attack. For example:  19...Nxb2  20.Qd2  Ba3  21.h5  And now a semi-forced line is   21...gxh5  22.Rxh5  Rfe8  23.Rbh1  Kf8  24.Rh8+  Ke7  25.Bg5+  f6  26.exf6+  gxf6  27.R1h7+  Kd8  28.Rxe8+  Kxe8  29.Ne5 !  with deadly threats.   The typical central break  14...f6 !?  15.exf6  gxf6  is quite weakening, and after  16.Re1  Kf7  17.Bf1  White has a big advantage. Nevertheless, this move manages to divert attention away from the strong h4-h5 break. } 15. a4 { Opening the a-file and making use of the rook on a1.   Instead  15.Kg2  , to follow with  Rh1  immediately, allows  15...cxd4  16.cxd4  Nb6  17.b3  Nb4  when the threat of  ...Nc2  diverts some attention away from the kingside, though White is still much better after  18.Bg5  !?. } 15... Qb6 { Or  15...c4  16.b4 !  closing the queenside, since  16...cxb3 ?  only benefits White after:  17.axb5  axb5  18.Qxb3  ± } 16. axb5 axb5 17. Kg2 c4 18. Ng5 Qd8 { Momentarily preventing h4-h5.   White is also much better after  18...Bxg5  19.Bxg5  b4  20.h5  Nf8  21.Rh1  gxh5  22.Bxh5  g6  23.Bg4  ± followed by an h-file invasion. } 19. Bg4 { ± Threatening 20.Bxe6. } 19... Bxg5 { The alternative  19...Nf8  is similar to the game after  20.Qf3  Bxg5  21.Bxg5  Qb6  22.h5  gxh5  23.Bxh5  Qb7  24.Rh1  ± threatening  25.Bxf7+.   The careless  19...b4 ?  loses to  20.Bxe6 !  fxe6  21.Nxe6  Qb6  22.Qg4  Kf7  23.Nf4. } 20. Bxg5 Qc7 21. Rh1 Nb6 22. h5 { Opening the h-file decisively. } 22... gxh5 23. Bxh5 Na4 { This is a standard move in Black’s ...c5-c4 plan, pressuring b2, but here Black is losing the race by several moves.   If  23...Nd8  , protecting the f7-pawn, then  24.Bg4  Rg8  25.Qc2 !  and the invasion on the h-file is decisive, for example:  25...Na4  26.Qh7  Kf8  27.Rh4  Nxb2  28.Rah1  b4  29.Qxg8+ !  Kxg8  30.Rh8# } 24. Bxf7+ { A decisive piece sacrifice; note how White’s e5-pawn plays an important role in many critical variations. } 24... Kxf7 25. Qf3+ Kg8 { If  25...Kg6  26.Bf6 !  Black is getting checkmated due to the threat of  Qg4+  and  Qxg7  , and  26...Kf7   26...gxf6  27. Qxf6#; or  26...Rcg8  27.Rxh8  Rxh8  28.Qg4+  Kf7  29.Qxg7+  Ke8  30.Qxc7  +-  27.Bd8+  loses the queen. } 26. Rxh8+ Kxh8 27. Rh1+ Kg8 28. Qh5 { A strong quiet move which decides the game due to the threat of 29.Bf6 with a mating net. } 28... Rf8 { The king cannot escape with  28...Kf8  due to  29.Qg6 !  threatening  Rh8  , and after  29...Kg8  30.Bf6 !  there is no defence against  31.Rh7. For example:  30...Qf7  31.Rh8+ !   28...Nxe5  loses to  29.Bf4 !  Rf8  30.Bxe5  Qe7  31.Qg6 !  followed by  Rh7. } 29. Bf6 { Black resigns as he is either getting mated or losing his queen.  29...Qc8   or  29...gxf6  30.Qh8+  Kf7  31.Qh7+  Ke8  32.Qxc7  30.Qh7+  Kf7  31.Qxg7+  Ke8  32.Rh7  Followed by  Qg6  and a quick mate.  Final remarks  1. The capture 10...hxg6 changed the nature of the position, as the h4-h5 break became stronger than the typical f4-f5 break.  2. Black’s biggest problem was an incorrect positional evaluation. White’s d4-pawn was well protected, and the plan ...c5-c4, ...b7-b5-b4 was far too slow against White’s h4-h5 break. If Black had realized this opposite-flank race was lost, he probably would have played 11...Qc7 in order to castle long.  3. In retrospect, I believe 14...f6 was a reasonable option. It certainly looks terrible as the pawns on e6, f6 and g6 make a very vulnerable team. However, by trading the e5-pawn White’s attacking chances are reduced and Black manages to stay in the game for longer. } *

