{ @@HeaderStart@@Sergei Zhigalko – Julian Radulski, Warsaw 2010@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game illustrates how Black may effectively carry out the ...c5-c4 plan, subsequently castling long and creating a kingside attack. } 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 { To play b2-b4, forcing Black to release the tension on d4. } 6... c4 { Now let’s see how the game continued. } 7. Nbd2 Na5 8. Be2 Bd7 9. O-O { Over the last couple of years the move  9.Rb1 !?  has become more popular, as White wants to open the b-file to have an attack once Black castles queenside. Recent games have continued with:  9...Ne7   but  9...Qc7 !?  is enough to prevent b2-b4 for the moment, obtaining a position similar to the game  10.b4  cxb3  11.Nxb3  The b-file is open, and now if Black attempts to win an exchange with  11...Ba4  then simply:  12.Nxa5 !  Qxa5   or  12...Bxd1 ?!  13.Rxb6  axb6  14.Bb5+  Kd8  15.Nxb7+  Kc7  16.Kxd1  Kxb7  17.Ng5  += as in the game Rapport – Apicella, France 2013  13.Qd2  b5  14.Bd3  a6  15.O-O  Rc8  16.Qe2  h6  17.Bd2  With a fighting position as in the game Duda – Wang Yiye, Al-Ain 2013. } 9... Ne7 10. Rb1 Qc7 11. Ne1 { Opening the b-file with  11.b4 ?  no longer works due to:  11...cxb3  12.Nxb3  Ba4  ∓   Another possible plan was  11.Re1  Nc8  12.Nf1  Nb6  13.Bf4  Ba4  14.Qc1  Nb3  15.Qe3  when Black’s king will be safe on the queenside but White will expand on the kingside anyway. However, the game will not be ”one-sided” as White’s kingside attack may become dangerous to his own king. Overall, chances are approximately equal as in the game Nakamura – Pelletier, Biel 2005. } 11... O-O-O 12. Bg4 Kb8 { But now: } 13. Nc2 { This is not the best way to proceed.   13.f4  was a better alternative, and after  13...g6  14.Ndf3  Bg7  15.Bh3  the position is complicated, but chances are approximately balanced. White must expand on the kingside with extreme care, so as not to allow strong counterplay. For example,  15...Rdg8  16.g4 ?  would certainly be a premature decision, since now  16...h5 !  gives Black an excellent game. } 13... Ba4 { A good and rather thematic move. This bishop permanently prevents White from obtaining queenside play, and now it also makes White’s manoeuvres more difficult due to the pin. } 14. Nf3 { To illustrate why the pin is annoying, notice that the normal  14.f4  can now be met by  14...h5 !?  15.Bh3   not  15.Bxh5 ?  Bxc2  16.Qxc2  Rxh5  and wins  15...Nf5  16.Nf3  Be7  with a good game for Black. } 14... Nc8 15. Qe2 Nb6 { This knight transfer is very typical of the position; it reinforces the control of the queenside, and may help in a future expansion. The position is critical and White needs to find the right way to react on the kingside. } 16. h4 { But this is not it, as we shall see.   It was better to play  16.Ng5 !?  improving the knight:  16...h6  17.Nh3  Be7  18.Nf4 !?   or  18.f4 !?  with a normal position  (Now the knight is pretty good on f4, as it makes it difficult for Black to play ...f7-f5)  (or ...f7-f6)  (and helps prepare a slow-paced kingside expansion with g2-g3 and h2-h4-h5.) } 16... Ka8 { This is a normal move, but it misses a stronger continuation.   A strong option was:  16...f5 !  17.Bh3   Or  17.exf6  gxf6  when Black can soon develop an unpleasant kingside initiative. The e6-pawn is untouchable since  18.Bxe6 ?  loses to  18...Re8  followed by  ...Bd7.  17...h6  Black will continue with  ...Be7  ,  ...Rdg8  and  ...g5  with an extremely powerful kingside attack. } 17. h5 { White does not realize how many problems he is about to face. In fact, this move makes Black’s reaction even stronger, as the h5-pawn will become a target.   Again  17.Ng5  would have prevented Black’s strong kingside reaction with  ...f7-f5  and after  17...h6  18.Nh3  g6  19.Bf4  the game is approximately balanced. } 17... f5 { A wonderful move! A double exclamation mark is not an exaggeration: the move is both strong and nearly decisive. This is a reaction the reader should never forget: by using a tactical resource, Black achieves the ...f7-f5 push, after which he dominates the game for the following reasons:  1. He clearly controls the queenside; he has nothing to fear on this flank.  2. He can now begin to expand on the kingside with an eventual ...g7-g5.   3. He can easily create an attack against White’s king.  4. White is inferior on both flanks, hence he cannot create counterplay. } 18. Bh3 { It is probably better to take on  f6  , in order to prevent Black’s kingside expansion with  ...g7-g5  , but in this case  18.exf6  gxf6  does not really help White either, since his position is so weakened:  19.Re1   not  19.Bxe6 ?  Re8  -+ followed by  ...Bd7  19...Re8  20.Bh3  Bd6  21.Ne3  Qf7  ∓ Black is about to create a strong attack down the g-file, and the h5-pawn is falling.   If  18.Ng5  fxg4  19.Nxe6  Qd7  20.Nxd8  Qxd8  ∓ the two pieces are far stronger than a rook in this position. } 18... Qf7 { Attacking the weak h5-pawn. } 19. Ng5 { If  19.h6  gxh6  Black is simply a pawn up, as the doubled h-pawns are quite useful. For example:  20.g3  Rg8  21.Kh2  Bxc2  22.Qxc2  Be7  23.Qe2   23.Bxh6 ?  loses a piece to  23...Qh5  23...Bg5  24.Rg1  Rdf8  ∓ With threats such as  ...f5-f4  or  ...Nb3. } 19... Qg8 20. Bf4 h6 21. Nf3 Qf7 { Even stronger was  21...Bxc2 !  22.Qxc2  Qf7  winning the h5-pawn and the game after  23.g3  Qxh5  24.Bg2  g5. } 22. Nfe1 Rg8 23. Kh1 Be7 24. Ne3 { White is struggling to manoeuvre, having little space.   More stubborn was  24.Bh2  Rdf8  25.f4  but after  25...g5  26.hxg6  Qxg6  ∓ White remains in deep trouble. } 24... Rdf8 { Preparing ...Be8 and ...Qxh5.   The premature  24...Be8  is answered by  25.g4  fxg4  26.Qxg4  though Black preserves an advantage after:  26...g5 !  27.Bh2  Qh7 !?  ∓ } 25. Bh2 Be8 26. g4 { Making things easier for Black.   The last attempt was  26.f4  Qxh5  27.g4 !  since after  27...Qxh3   or  27...Qg6 !?  ∓  the queen gets trapped:  28.Rf3  Qh4  29.N1g2  But even so Black is better after  29...fxg4  30.Nxh4  gxf3  31.Nxf3  g5  ∓ with the strong threat of  ...Bg6-e4. } 26... f4 27. N3c2 f3 28. Qd1 g6 { Black opens the kingside decisively. } 29. hxg6 Qxg6 30. Rg1 { 30.Nxf3  doesn’t help due to  30...Rxf3  31.Qxf3  Qxc2. } 30... Ba4 { All of White’s forces are tied up. } 31. g5 { Other choices are no better.   For example:  31.Rg3  Bh4  32.Rxf3  Bxf2  33.Rxf8+  Rxf8  34.Qe2  Bxe1  -+ } 31... hxg5 { The h-file will be fatal for White; he simply does not have sufficient space to reorganize his forces. } 32. Rg3 Rh8 33. Bg4 Rh4 34. Rc1 Qe4 35. Bxf3 Qh7 { White had to resign.  Final remarks  1. The ...c5-c4 advance by Black had to be combined with long castling, and works especially well if White is unable to open the b-file with b2-b3.   2. Once Black has castled long, White may still expand on the kingside, but there is a chance this plan could backfire as White’s king can now become exposed.  3. Black’s 17th move ...f5 was an extremely strong blow. If Black manages to combine ...c5-c4 with the ...f7-f5 advance, then he has obtained a significant spatial advantage and White is in serious trouble all over the board. It is no surprise that Black was able to win easily afterwards, as there is little White can do to prevent Black’s active kingside play based on the ...g7-g5 expansion. } *

