{ @@HeaderStart@@Nguyen Van Huy – Le Quang Liem, Ho Chi Minh City 2012@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game illustrates Black’s minority attack. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 b5 5. O-O Nbd7 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Nbd2 c5 8. dxc5 Nxc5 { After White’s unambitious opening, we have a Slav formation with reversed colours. White needs a central break to avoid being inferior. } 9. Nd4 Bd7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. e4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Bxe4 Rb8 { We have reached the structure of interest. Black is doing well for two reasons:  1. He has the pair of bishops in an open position.  2. His b5-pawn is ready for a minority attack; White will be unable to expand his queenside majority without it being weakened. } 15. Qd3 { Eliminating Black’s bishop pair with  15.Nc6 ?  Bxc6  16.Bxc6  loses a pawn after  16...b4 !  17.Qxd8  Rfxd8  18.cxb4  Rxb4  ∓ when the b2-pawn is lost. } 15... h6 16. Rad1 { Of course  16.b3 ?  (to create a passed pawn with c3-c4)  is simply met by  16...Qc7  17.c4  bxc4  18.bxc4  Rfc8  ∓ when the c4-pawn is a weakness and not a strength. } 16... Qc7 17. a3 Rfc8 18. Qf3 { Without being able to expand, White can only run on the spot, waiting for Black to act.   Attempting kingside action with  18.f4  a5  19.f5  e5  does not help White, and after  20.Nc2  Bc6 !?  21.Ne3  b4 !  22.Bxc6  Qxc6  23.axb4  axb4  24.c4  Bd8 !  =+ Black will follow up with  ...Bb6  and White’s king will become vulnerable. } 18... a5 19. Rd3 { White should have fought harder to avoid the ...b5-b4 break.   Better was  19.Nc2  Be8  20.Qe2  Be7  =+   or  20...Rd8 !?  (though the ...b5-b4 break will come sooner or later.) } 19... Be8 20. Rfd1 b4 { The minority attack has been completed; White will be left with a weak pawn on the queenside. } 21. axb4 axb4 22. cxb4 Rxb4 23. Rc3 { If  23.b3  Qb6  24.Ne2  Bg5 !?  ∓ White must deal with the weak b3-pawn as well as his misplaced pieces; one threat is  ...f5. } 23... Qb8 24. Nc6 Bxc6 25. Rxc6 Rxc6 26. Bxc6 Rxb2 { The minority attack has succeeded, Black has gained a pawn and now he must try to win the 4 vs. 3 battle on the kingside. } 27. Ra1 { Did White want to trade rooks and queens even at the cost of a second pawn?   Better was  27.Rd7 !  Qe5  28.Kg2  g6  ∓ though Black may make progress slowly. } 27... Rxf2 28. Ra8 Qxa8 29. Bxa8 Rxf3 30. Bxf3 { We have an opposite-coloured bishop endgame, but as it turns out, two connected pawns are often enough to win such an endgame as long as there are more pawns on the board. } 30... Bd4+ 31. Kg2 g6 32. Bd1 f5 33. h4 { Another try was:  33.g4  Kf7  34.gxf5  gxf5  35.Kf3  e5  36.Bc2  Attempting to build a fortress and sacrifice the bishop for two pawns when needed:  36...Kf6   Of course not  36...e4+ ?  37.Bxe4  fxe4+  38.Kxe4  which is a theoretical draw, because the bishop is on squares of the wrong colour.  37.Bd3  Kg5  38.Bc2  Ba7 !  39.h4+   Or  39.Bb1  e4+ !  40.Bxe4  fxe4+  41.Kxe4  Kg4  and Black wins.  39...Kg6  40.Bb1  Bb6  41.Bc2  Bd8 !  This is the key.   42.h5+  Kg5  43.Bb1  Bb6  44.Bc2  e4+  45.Bxe4  fxe4+  46.Kxe4  Kg4 !   But not  46...Kxh5 ??  47.Kf3  and draws.  47.Kd3  Kxh5  48.Ke2  Kg4  49.Kf1  Kf3  And Black wins. } 33... h5 34. Ba4 Kf7 35. Kf3 Bb6 36. Bb5 Ba5 37. Bc6 Be1 38. Kf4 e5+ 39. Kf3 { Or  39.Kxe5  Bxg3+  40.Kd5  Bxh4  and wins. } 39... g5 { Now Black wraps up the game very nicely. } 40. hxg5 Kg6 41. Kg2 Kxg5 42. Kh3 { Also hopeless is  42.Bd5  e4 !  43.Bc6  h4  44.gxh4+  Bxh4. } 42... h4 43. gxh4+ Bxh4 { Even though there are only two pawns left, Black is winning because White does not have enough time to set up the standard defence with Kf3 and Bd3. } 44. Kg2 e4 45. Kf1 Kf6 46. Ke2 Ke5 47. Be8 f4 { White resigns.   48.Bh5  is inadequate as  48...Kf5 !  places White in zugzwang:  49.Kd2  f3  50.Ke3  Bg5+  51.Kf2  Kf4  -+  Final remarks  1. Black’s bishop pair proved very useful, as White had no entry points on the d-file and could not create counterplay with it.  2. A red flag for White should have been the b5-pawn, which hinted that a queenside expansion would not be achievable hence White should stay passive.  3. White’s biggest problem in this game was his rather questionable opening, which left him fighting for equality from the very beginning. Black’s play was impeccable. } *

