{ @@HeaderStart@@Black’s counterplay against the d4-pawn@@HeaderEnd@@  The position in the diagram occurred in the game Getz – Istratescu, Oslo 2013. Black began to obtain counterplay with: } 1... Ne4 { The first part of the plan; this knight disrupts White’s coordination. } 2. Bb2 { But not:  14.Nxe4 ?  dxe4  15.Bxd7   or  15.Ne5  Bxb5  16.Qxb5  Qxd4  ∓  15...exf3  16.Qc4  Qxd7  17.Qxb4  fxg2  ∓ } 2... Bxb5 3. Nxb5 Nc6 { The second part in Black’s plan, pressuring the d4-pawn. } 4. Nc3 f5 { Now the third part, supporting the knight on e4 and preparing the last part of the plan: ...Bf6 with substantial pressure on d4. } 5. Nxe4 { If  17.Rab1  Bf6  18.Rfd1  Qd7  19.Ba1  Rab8  and Black is at least equal. } 5... dxe4 { 17...fxe4 !?  was promising too, for example  18.Nd2  Rb8  19.Bc3  e5 !?  20.Nb3  exd4  21.Nxd4  Qd7  =+ when the c5-pawn is very weak. } 6. Qc4 { Or:  18.Rfd1  Qd5 !   but not  18...exf3 ?  19.Qxe6+  Kh8  20.Qxc6  ±  19.Ne5  Nxe5  20.dxe5  Qxc5  =+ } 6... Qd5 7. Qxd5 exd5 8. Ne1 Rab8 9. Bc3 Bf6 10. Nc2 f4 { Black had a very promising position and eventually won the game. } *

