{ @@HeaderStart@@Black’s ...b7-b6 counterplay@@HeaderEnd@@  The position in the diagram occurred in the game Klundt – Dautov, Bad Wiessee 2001. In order to avoid the long-term problems Black faced in Dreev – Galic, Black modified the structure immediately with: } 1... Nxc3 2. bxc3 h6 3. O-O b6 { This is the key; now Black is rid of his backward b7-pawn and forces White to have a backward c3-pawn. } 4. Rfb1 Ba6 { If light-squared bishops are off the board, then even better!   But not  15...bxc5 ?!  16.Rb5  Qc7  17.Rxc5  Qd6  18.Rb1  as White is a little better coordinated. } 5. Bxa6 Qxa6 6. cxb6 { Imprecise.   Better was  17.Ne5 !  Rfc8   or  17...bxc5 !?  18.Nd7  cxd4  19.Nxf8  d3  20.Qd2  Rxf8  =∞  18.Nd3 =  when it is hard for Black to pressure the c3-pawn. } 6... axb6 7. Qb3 Rfc8 { Black is better as both the c3- and a2-pawns are clear targets. This kind of position is exactly what Black is looking for when he plays the ...b7-b6 break. White’s once-powerful queenside majority is now just a weakness. } *

