{ @@HeaderStart@@Converting a Carlsbad into a Panov structure@@HeaderEnd@@  The position in the diagram occurred in the game Rahman – Areshchenko, Chennai 2011. If play develops slowly, Black could find himself in an inferior version of the Carlsbad because his c6-pawn is weakened, as he has already played ...b7-b6. Thus Black takes a good opportunity to transform the structure with: } 1... c5 2. Bf3 { The greater of two evils.   If  14.dxc5  Nxc5  15.Qc2   or  15.Qa3  Bf8 !?  =+  15...Rc8  16.Nf3  a6  17.Be1  b5  =+ Black has a very comfortable isolani. } 2... c4 { The game continued: } 3. Qc2 a6 4. b3 b5 5. bxc4 bxc4 6. Rb1 Qc7 7. Qc1 Nf8 { =+ Black has a very pleasant position; he is preparing ...Ne6-g5.  Black eventually won, though this is not particularly relevant to us. What we have learned is how a Carlsbad structure can transpose into a Panov structure. } *

