{ @@HeaderStart@@Mauricio Flores Rios – Rodrigo Vasquez, Reno  (rapid)  2007@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game is an example of the sharp complications that may arise after Black’s ...d6-d5 break. } 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e6 7. f3 b5 8. g4 { The purpose of this early g2-g4   instead of  8.Qd2  is to provoke: } 8... h6 { This move can be weakening in some cases. } 9. Qd2 Nbd7 10. O-O-O { Black decides to go for the sharp continuation: } 10... b4 11. Na4 d5 { Achieving the standard ...d6-d5 break, but while Black’s king is still in the centre. } 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Bc4 { White is playing aggressively and maximum precision is required. If Black manages to stabilize his position and castle, then he is probably going to take the lead. } 13... Bb7 14. Rhe1 Qa5 { An overly optimistic move.   The careless  14...Nxe3 ?  loses after  15.Nxe6 !  fxe6  16.Bxe6  Bc6  17.Qxe3.   Safer was  14...N7f6  15.g5  hxg5  16.Bxg5  though after  16...Be7  as in Negi – David, Belgium 2012, then  17.Nxe6 !  fxe6  18.Rxe6  gives White a promising position since  18...O-O  is met by  19.Qe2 !  Rf7  20.Bxf6  Bxf6  21.Nb6  winning a decisive amount of material. } 15. Nxe6 { +- This was only a twenty-minute game and I could not calculate much; all I knew was that the nature of the position called for an aggressive move like this one, preserving the initiative.   If  15.Bb3 ?  O-O-O  ∞ Black is comfortable and White no longer has clear targets to attack. } 15... fxe6 16. Bb6 { Attacking e6 while covering the d8-square, thus preventing Black’s king from escaping with ...O-O-O.   So of course not  16.Bf2 ?  O-O-O. } 16... Qxa4 { White is also winning after:  16...N7xb6  17.Rxe6+  Be7   or  17...Kd7  18.Nxb6+  Kxe6  19.Nxd5  +-;  17...Kf7  18.Rxb6  +-  18.Nxb6  O-O   or  18...Nxb6  19.Rxe7+ !  Kxe7  20.Qd6+  Ke8  21.Qe6+  Kf8  22.Qf7#  19.Rxe7  Qxb6  20.Rxb7 !   16...N5xb6  17.Rxe6+  Be7  18.Nxb6  transposes to the variation above. } 17. Bxd5 Be7 { 17...Nxb6  is met decisively by:  18.Rxe6+  Be7  19.Rxe7+ !  Kxe7  20.Qe3+  Kd7  21.Qxb6  Bxd5  22.Rxd5+ } 18. Rxe6 Bxd5 { Again  18...Nxb6  loses to  19.Rxe7+ !  as above. } 19. Qxd5 Nxb6 { If  19...Rc8  20.Rxe7+ !  Kxe7  21.Re1+  White has a forced mate, for example:  21...Kf8  22.Bc5+  Nxc5  23.Qf5+  Kg8  24.Qxc8+  Kh7  25.Qf5+  Kg8  26.Re7 ! } 20. Rxb6 Rd8 21. Qh5+ Kf8 22. Qf5+ Kg8 { Or  22...Ke8  23.Qg6+ !  Kf8  24.Rxd8+  Bxd8  25.Rb7  forcing mate. } 23. Rxd8+ Bxd8 24. Qd5+ Kh7 25. Qd3+ { Quicker and nicer was:  25.Rxh6+ !  Kxh6   25...gxh6  26.Qf7#  26.Qh5#   After  25.Qd3+  Black resigned because he is losing a rook after  25...Kg8  26.Qxd8+  Kh7  27.Qd3+  Kg8  28.Rb8+  Kf7  29.Rxh8.  Final remarks  It is dangerous for Black to carry out the ...d6-d5 break before castling. The resulting position is rather complicated, but seems favourable to White as long as he is ready to sacrifice material when appropriate. } *

