{ @@HeaderStart@@Isam Ortiz Suarez – Manuel Leon Hoyos, Havana 2011@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game illustrates how Black’s queenside initiative develops when White fails to create a fortress or a central break. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bxa6 7. g3 d6 8. Bg2 Bg7 9. Nf3 Nbd7 10. O-O Nb6 11. Nh4 { The idea behind this relatively rare move is to protect the d5-pawn, in order to move the queen to c2 next.   Much more common is  11.Re1. } 11... O-O 12. Rb1 { Instead  12.Qc2  seems more precise, since now  12...Nc4 ?!  is met by  13.b3  Ne5  14.Bb2  with a stable position   though after  12.Qc2  Nfd7  13.Rd1  Qc7  14.Rb1  Nc4  15.b3 ?!  Qa5 !  =+ Black is doing very well. } 12... Nc4 13. Qc2 { If  13.b3  then Black has time for  13...Qa5 !  since after:  14.Qc2   14.bxc4 ?  Qxc3  ∓  14...Na3  15.Bxa3  Qxa3  Black is ready to regain the pawn, say after:  16.Nf3  Nd7  17.Rfc1   but not  17.Ra1 ?!  c4 !  18.Rfc1  Rfc8  ∓  17...Bxc3  18.Qxc3  Bxe2  =+ } 13... Qa5 14. a4 { White is trying to play b2-b3 to build a queenside fortress, but now: } 14... Nd7 { =+ This strong continuation threatens 15...Na3. } 15. Na2 { The careless  15.Rd1 ?  is met by:  15...Na3 !  16.bxa3  Qxc3  17.Qxc3  Bxc3  ∓   15.Nd1  Rfb8  16.b3  Qb6 !  is also unpleasant for White, say after  17.Nf3  Na5  18.Bg5  h6 !  19.Be3   but not  19.Bxe7 ?  Re8  20.Bh4  Rxe2  -+  19...Nf6  =+ and the b3-pawn will fall sooner or later. } 15... Ncb6 { A strong reply, attacking the a4-pawn and inviting b2-b3. } 16. Bg5 { Black is also better after:  16.b3  c4  17.b4  Qxa4  18.Qd2  Ne5  19.Nc3  Qd7  =+ } 16... Nxa4 { Black’s strategy has clearly succeeded, as he has recovered the pawn while maintaining the pressure on the queenside. It is clear that the pawn on b2 is weak while the c5-pawn is not.   Even better was  16...Qxa4 !  17.Qxa4  Nxa4  as after  18.Bxe7  Rfe8  19.Bxd6  Bxe2  20.Rfe1  Bd3 !  White is losing too much material after:  21.Rbc1  Bxb2  22.Rcd1  Bc4  23.Nc1  Nc3 !  -+ } 17. Rfc1 { Again, White must avoid  17.Bxe7 ?  Rfe8  18.Bg5  Rxe2. } 17... Bb5 18. Bf1 Rfe8 19. Bd2 Qa6 20. b4 { Or  20.Nc3  Nxc3  21.Bxc3  Bxc3  22.bxc3  Bc4 !  attacking the d5-pawn, and after  23.e4  Ne5  24.Kg2  Bxf1+  25.Rxf1  Qc4 !  White is lost, due to his vulnerable c3- and e4-pawns. } 20... Rec8 { ∓ } 21. Qe4 { If  21.bxc5  Rxc5  the position is almost symmetrical, but White cannot avoid losing material due to Black’s superior coordination. For example,  22.Qd1  Nb2  23.Nb4  Nxd1  24.Nxa6  Bxa6  25.Rxd1  Nf6  ∓ when the d5-pawn is lost. } 21... Nf6 22. Qf3 { After  22.Qxe7 ?  Re8  23.Qc7  Nxd5  24.Qa5  Qc6  White is lost as the queen is trapped. } 22... Bc4 { White’s position collapses as the knight on a2 and the pawn on d5 are under attack. The rest is easy. } 23. Nc3 Nxc3 24. Bxc3 Nxd5 25. Bxg7 Kxg7 26. b5 Qa4 27. b6 Rcb8 28. b7 Ra7 29. e4 Bxf1 30. exd5 Ba6 31. Ra1 Qd4 32. Ra3 Rbxb7 33. Rca1 Rb6 34. h3 Qc4 { Final remarks  1. White’s strategy failed right from the opening, as he did not even get the time to play b2-b3 and a2-a4, and he was already facing serious threats.  2. Something remarkable about the Benko structure is how once Black regains the pawn, essentially all nearly-symmetrical positions favour Black. We see this very clearly in the notes to 20.Nc3 and 21.bxc5. Of course, Black’s problem is I should not say ”once” he regains the pawn, but ”if” he regains the pawn. } *

