{ @@HeaderStart@@David Navara – Ivan Sokolov, Reykjavik 2012@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objectives:  1. This game is an example of Black’s central counterplay after a double pawn trade on d4.   2. Note how the e4-pawn becomes a serious target before White can organize an attack against the technically weak d6-pawn. } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O Nf6 6. Re1 Bd7 7. c3 g6 8. d4 b5 9. Bb3 Bg7 { So far we are following a standard variation of the Deferred Steinitz Variation, and now: } 10. Bg5 { This is the beginning of a bad plan.   Instead  10.h3  O-O  11.Nbd2  h6  12.Nf1  Re8  13.Ng3  is a healthier approach, since the bishop is more useful on  c1  than on  h4. } 10... O-O 11. Nbd2 Re8 12. h3 h6 13. Bh4 { White’s bishop will be quite useless on this square.   Better was  13.Be3 !  since  13...exd4 ?!  14.cxd4  Nxe4 ?  is met by:  15.Nxe4  Rxe4  16.Qc2 !  Re7   or  16...Qe8  17.Bxh6 !  ±  17.Qxg6 !  ± } 13... Na5 14. Bc2 c5 { And we have obtained our Lopez Formation. Black has made a good choice since he is well prepared if White closes the centre with d4-d5. In addition, the move 14...c5 allows ...Qc7, moving away from the pin and leaving the bishop on h4 doing nothing. } 15. Nb3 { A strange choice that is too slow for the position.   Instead  15.d5  Qc7  gives Black a good position, as his fianchettoed bishop makes for an impenetrable kingside. Meanwhile, White’s dark-squared bishop is somewhat misplaced. A possible continuation was  16.Bxf6   or  16.Nf1  Nh5  16...Bxf6  17.Nf1  Bg7  18.Ne3  Rf8  when Black plans  ...f7-f5  with good kingside play.   If  15.dxc5  dxc5  16.Nf1  Qc7  17.Ne3  Be6  Black is not worse, as his queenside has already expanded while the d5-square is protected. } 15... cxd4 16. Nxa5 { An option was  16.cxd4  exd4  17.Nbxd4  Qb6  though Black is very comfortable and active. For example:  18.Bg3   or  18.a4  Nh5 !  threatening  ...g5  18...Nc4  19.Rb1   or  19.b3  Na3  =+  19...Rad8   or  19...Bc8 !?  followed by  ...Bb7  attacking  e4  And now White is defenceless against the threat of  20...d5  , for example:  20.a4  d5  21.e5  Ne4 !  ∓ } 16... Qxa5 17. cxd4 exd4 { A good decision, opening the position and taking advantage of White’s poorly-arranged pieces. } 18. Nxd4 { 18.Qxd4  is met by  18...g5 !  19.Bg3  Nxe4  20.Be5  dxe5  21.Qxe4  Qc7  =+ when White’s compensation is quite insufficient. } 18... Qb6 { We have reached a critical position and it is time to make an assessment. In the long term White should have a huge advantage because the d6-pawn is a weak isolated backward pawn – an easy target. However, Black’s pieces are arranged so well that it is not clear White will have a long term! Black’s bishop is extremely powerful along the h8-a1 diagonal, pressuring the knight on d4 and the pawn on b2. Meanwhile, White’s bishop on h4 is rather useless and would have been far better placed on b2 or e3.   When Black decides to trade both pawns on d4, he must carefully assess whether he will have enough counterplay to compensate for the weak d6-pawn. In this case, Black has made an excellent choice and in fact, he is already better. } 19. Nf3 Be6 { Clearing d7 for the knight. } 20. Nd4 { Or  20.Qd2  Nd7  21.Bd1  Rac8  22.Bg3  Nc5  23.Rc1  Qb7  24.Bc2  d5 !  trading the weak d6-pawn:  25.exd5  Bxd5  =+ } 20... Bc8 { Now the bishop is heading to b7, and suddenly the e4-pawn is far weaker than the d6-pawn. } 21. Qd2 { Correct was:  21.Ne2 !  Bb7   not  21...Nxe4 ?  22.Nf4 !  and White gains counterplay, for example:  22...Bb7  23.Nd5  Bxd5  24.Qxd5  Nf6  25.Bxf6  Bxf6  26.Bxg6 !  +=  22.Nc3  Now after either  22...Rac8  =+   or  22...d5 !?  (Black preserves a comfortable position.) } 21... Bb7 22. Bxf6 { 22.f3 ?  is met by:  22...Nxe4 !  23.Bxe4  Qxd4+  ∓ } 22... Bxf6 23. Rad1 { The last mistake.   White puts up a better fight after  23.Nf3 !  Rac8 !   but not  23...Bxb2 ?!  24.Qxh6 !  with good compensation  24.Bb3  Kg7  ∓ when White’s pawns on  e4  and  b2  are vulnerable. } 23... d5 { -+ The ‘weak’ d6-pawn arrives to decide the game. Black is winning a pawn with a decisive advantage. } 24. Bb3 { The point is that  24.exd5 ?  loses a piece after  24...Rxe1+  25.Rxe1  Bxd4.   24.e5  is also inadequate:  24...Bxe5  25.Nf3  Bg7  26.Bb3  d4 !  -+ } 24... Rxe4 25. Rxe4 dxe4 26. Nf5 { A good try in a lost position. } 26... Rd8 { But not  26...gxf5 ?  27.Qxh6 !  when Black has nothing better than a draw after:  27...Bd4  28.Qg5+  Kh8   28...Kf8 ?!  29.Qxf5  +=  29.Qh5+  Kg8  30.Qg5+ = } 27. Nxh6+ { Instantly hopeless is  27.Qxh6 ?  Rxd1+  28.Bxd1  gxf5. } 27... Kg7 28. Qc1 Rxd1+ 29. Bxd1 e3 { Winning a decisive tempo by attacking the knight. } 30. Ng4 exf2+ 31. Kf1 Bd4 { The rest is simple. } 32. Qh6+ Kg8 33. Qf4 Qc6 34. Bf3 Qc4+ 35. Be2 Bxg2+ 36. Kxg2 Qxe2 37. Nh6+ Kh7 { Final remarks  1. The d6-pawn was never a weakness. Instead, the e4-pawn was quite vulnerable, since playing f2-f3 would severely weaken the g1-a7 diagonal.  2. One of White’s biggest problems was not having the dark-squared bishop on b2 or e3, to parry the threats.  3. Black’s counterplay was particularly successful because of White’s poor coordination. The double pawn trade on d4 would not work as well if White could manage to stabilize the position. } *

